projectInfo.name: Jeremie - Mapping of the unsafe places based on gender - Women Connect Challenge - Haiti
projectInfo.shortDescription: This project is led by CARE Haiti et CartONG and aims to map - according to a collaborative approach - the places that youth and women communities consider as unsafe in 7 neighborhoods of the City of Jeremie.
projectInfo.description:
This project is led by CARE and CartONG and aims to map unsafe or high-risk places of gender-based violence in the city of Jérémie. This mapping will be done initially in a participatory approach that will - in several stages - determine the causes, frequency, severity and consequences of insecurity in the city of Jérémie in order to address later tracks improvement to the authorities. This mapping by and for the local population can then be valued by the actors of security and justice of the city as well as the local population on a larger scale.

In order for the women and youth communities to find their mark on the map during the workshops, we would like to use the most complete OpenStreetMap basemap possible. For this we need to precisely locate the buildings and roads in 7 districts of the city of Jérémie where intervene the teams of CARE: Lower Town; Plato; Deye Teren; Saint Helena; Morne Fort; Caracol; Caracola II.
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Imagery ============ You will use **Drone Imagery Matthew (Haiti) October 2016** pour cette zone. 2. Buildings ============ On this project, there are already many buildings that have been mapped, but you will see that there is sometimes a significant gap between the elements already on the map and the imagery we use. Try to move the buildings as precisely as possible and remove those who have completely disappeared. Buildings destroyed but still visible on the imagery must be mapped as a building under construction (since most will be rebuilt on the same foundations). ![BEFORE] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/BEFORE%20Jeremy_resizeimage.jpg) ![AFTER] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/AFTER%20Jeremy_resizeimage.jpg) * **Draw all the buildings you see, including the foundations of the destroyed buildings (as "under construction" so we can easily identify them).** * **Be as precise as possible !** _Zoom to distinguish the buildings. Trace it in full even though it is partially covered by trees on the satellite image._ --- ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* 1. The first time you draw a building, unfold in the menu on the left the category**« Building features »**, and select **« Building »** (it is the most generic tag that we can use because we can not know the more specific use of a building from the only aerial imagery), OR type "Building under construction" (in the search box on the top left) for destroyed buildings. 2. Then correct the angles by pressing the key **"S"** ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With JOSM Editor:* 1. Draw the building and add the tag **building=yes** OR the tag **building=construction** if it is a building under construction. `Warning: Many buildings are very close but in fact do not touch each other, try to draw them close to each other but without connecting them or sharing knots with other buildings, roads or contours of residential areas. In the iD web editor, when you press the Alt key, you will prevent the nodes from sticking to each other or attaching themselves to a nearby path to accidentally connect to them.` --- 3. Road network ============ Most of the city's roads are already mapped. So there is not much work left. You can complete the network if needed and draw the missing paths. * **Please draw the most clearly identifiable roads and paths** * **Connect roads to existing network** whenever possible. * **Very short segments that do not connect to anything should not be mapped** * **Most roads are already very well referenced. If the drawingis not correct, you can modify it by clicking on the road and moving the points, one by one.** * **Overflow slightly from your square** so that the person who will be working on a square next yo yours can easily connect to it. ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* * Once you have drawn a road, for this specific project, you will use the category **« Road features »**, and select the tag **« Residential road »**. * Once you have drawn a road, for this specific project, you will use the category **« Road features »**, and select the tag **« Unmaintained Track road »**. *With JOSM:* * Draw the road and add the tag **highway=path**. --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain permanently in the OSM database and visible and reusable by all. So be as specific as possible ! **Quality is more important than quantity!** Remember that mapping requires patience, attention and care.

**If you have any questions, please put them in the comment section**, one of our validators will be happy to answer them !
